Five truths about terrorism
SÃO PAULO – American policy is being held hostage by terrorism.
In December 2015, polls indicated that one in six Americans, or approximately 16% of the population, now ranked terrorism as the top issue facing the country – a 3% increase in just one month.
For the first time in a decade, no Americans have ever been this concerned about terrorism, although their number remains still far below the 46% recorded in the aftermath of the September 11, 2001 attacks.
The consequences of this shift in public opinion were most evident during the Republican primary for the presidential election.
The candidacy of Donald Trump, whose anti-Muslim rhetoric was particularly inflammatory (if not incendiary), certainly benefited from this.
Certain politicians have authorized themselves to speak of the battle against terrorism as the "Third World War".
The terrorism is a problem for the United States, as shown by the San Bernardino attack, in California, in the month of December of last year.
But the candidates in the presidential election, just like some media outlets, who are fond of the old adage "if it bleeds, it's on the front page," have exaggerated the proportions.
To put terrorism in its true perspective, Americans should – like others – have the following considerations in mind.
The terrorism is a kind of theater.
The terrorists worry more about holding the attention and dominating the political agenda than the number, in itself, of their victims.
The Islamic State (ISIS) takes great care of its stage presence.
The barbaric beheadings broadcast on social media are intended to destabilize and scandalize – and thus to monopolize attention.
Exaggerating their consequences and making headlines with each terrorist action is playing the terrorists' game.
Terrorism is not the most severe threat looming over the populations of developed countries.
Terrorism kills far fewer people than car accidents or smoking.
From this perspective, terrorism is not even a genuine threat – neither major nor minor.
You are more likely to be struck by lightning than killed by a terrorist.
The probability that an American citizen will be killed by a terrorist is, according to experts, one in 3.5 million.
Americans are more likely to die in their bathtub (a probability of one in 950,000), from an appliance accident (a probability of one in 1.5 million), from a deer or elk crossing the road (a probability of one in 2 million), or in a commercial airliner crash (a probability of one in 2.9 million).
Six thousand Americans die every year driving while texting or talking on their phone.
It's several hundred times the number of those who die from terrorism.
Radical Islamic terrorism kills fewer Americans than workplace attacks or mass shootings at universities or schools.
Terrorism is not the Third World War.
Global terrorism is not a new phenomenon.
It often takes a generation to extinguish a terrorist blaze.
At the beginning of the 20th century, the anarchist movement killed a certain number of heads of state in the name of utopian ideals.
During the 1960s and 1970s, the Red Brigades and the Red Army Faction, both from the autonomous left, hijacked planes beyond national borders and kidnapped or killed business leaders or political leaders (as well as ordinary citizens).
Modern-day extremist jihadists are a longstanding political phenomenon dressed in a religious cloak.
Many of their leaders are not traditional fundamentalists, but rather people whose identities have been destroyed by globalization, seeking meaning in the imagined and pure community of an Islamic caliphate.
It will take time and effort to defeat them, but the ISIS's restrictive nature limits its scope of appeal.
His sectarian attacks already prevent him from addressing all Muslims, and a fortiori from addressing Hindus, Christians, or other believers.
ISIS will ultimately be defeated, just as were the transnational terrorist movements that preceded it.
Terrorism is like judo, as it uses an opponent's strength against them.
The weaker of the two opponents uses the strength of the stronger to defeat them.
No terrorist organization has the power of a state, and few terrorist movements have managed to overthrow one.
But if they succeed in shocking and provoking enough citizens of a state to push them to futile actions, they can hope to gain the upper hand.
In 2001, Al-Qaeda was able to draw the Americans to Afghanistan.
ISIS was born in the aftermath of the US-led invasion of Iraq, which followed the intervention in Afghanistan.
To defeat terrorism, we need a smart power.
A smart power is capable of combining the coercive power (hard power) of the army and the police with the influential power (soft power) of seduction and persuasion.
Influential power is also necessary if one wants to immunize those on the periphery and prevent the irreducible from recruiting.
That's why attention paid to the narrative of events and how the actions of the United States are commented on social media is just as important and necessary as precision airstrikes.
The rhetoric of confrontation, which points fingers at Muslims and alienates the goodwill that would allow us to obtain crucial information, puts us all in danger.
That's why the anti-Islam stance of some of the current presidential election candidates is so counterproductive.
The terrorism issue is serious, and it deserves to be placed among the priorities of our intelligence and police services, our armed forces, and our diplomacy.
She is an important factor in our foreign policy.
And it is essential to keep out of reach of terrorists the weapons of mass destruction.
But we must not fall into the trap set by the terrorists.
Let's not fill the stage with the actions of thugs and hoodlums.
If we abandon the main stage of our public discourse to them, we will diminish the quality of our civic life and reveal our priorities.
Our strength would then be turned against us.
